      </accessrestrict>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_01adeb15ecc88d81a528c1739dac7785">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Gift of Yale Dance Lab, 2023.</p>
      </acqinfo>
      <bioghist id="aspace_81de008e8444975cb3ba650a8b5c28b3">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Launched in 2021 by the Yale Dance Lab, the New Haven Dance History Project documents the city's diverse dance history. Led by researchers Gabrielle Niederhoffer and Jeffrey Steele--and under lead investigator Emily Coates--the project features thirty-three oral histories from local artists and contributors.</p>
         <p>The goal of this project is to preserve the undocumented cultural history of dance for many generations to come--it highlights the role of dance especially in public schools, local studios, and the New Haven, CT community at large.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_2c038c1787843d8ed127c5aabd338d9c">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>New Haven Dance Oral Histories collection. General Collection, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_95060f4e6f4388d8f3016ee82ca0c1ce">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>This collection includes video and audio recordings of oral histories created an collected during the New Haven Dance History Project. Other materials include scans of posters, programs, photographs, and other visual papers.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_64190e9756350c84635793489834069f">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>The New Haven Dance Oral Histories collection is the physical property of the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University. Literary rights, including copyright, belong to the authors or their legal heirs and assigns. For further information, consult the appropriate curator.</p>
      </userestrict>
